./.title: General Help
./.body:
Welcome to Beawre Risk Control
Efficient construction project design and execution depends on many different aspects including conforming to strict regulations and coordination of different stakeholders, tight budgets and strict deadlines. In particular, management of construction documents is an unavoidable and complex part of any project. Poor documentation control can lead to costly mistakes in execution. For example, a change in the project schedule may impact important deadlines, subcontractors may be late or they may not deliver expected quality, or clients may take longer than expected to review and approve documents.
All these aspects make it challenging to control the risks associated with documentation management. This is generally aggravated by the widespread use of spreadsheets that require manual management and generate processes that are prone to human error. Beawre Document Risk Control provides a smart solution to help you control risks related to documentation control.
With Beawre Risk Control, we acknowledge that managing risks in complex processes involving different stakeholders and platforms is difficult and we tackle three main challenges:

Control of activities owned by third parties
Software tools which are not prepared to support decision-making processes
Lack of interoperability between software platforms.

Summary of main features
Find out the main features that will help your organization optimize documentation review and approval processes. With Beawre Risk Control tools, you can efficiently control your work procedures, your projects and your organization.

Control subcontractors and efficiently coordinate with your client: See clearly if there is a risk of a subcontractor delivering documents late or if your customer is taking too long to approve documents using historical data.
Prioritize work based on the level of risk and focus on relevant tasks: What are the most risky documents I should be focusing on? Our algorithms automatically calculate the level of risk per document and show it in the documentation schedule.
Connect your project schedule with your documentation: Using different tools to manage your project schedule and your documentation schedule? Connect tools through our portal and have global control of the impact of changes in the documentation schedule or the consequences of delays in any document.
Build the documentation schedule collaboratively with subcontractors: Replace difficult-to-trace e-mail conversations and multiple spreadsheet versions with our collaborative options to help your subcontractor build their documentation schedules with you.
Leverage AI to enable smart analytics and prediction: Learn from your past activity and data and be better prepared for decision making. Use information to keep your subcontractors accountable. Leverage machine learning techniques to predict the future, anticipate unwanted situations and mitigate risks and potential negative impact.
Get automatic alerts to help you mitigate risks as soon as possible: Receive automated alerts in the form of messages or e-mails under defined circumstances where documentation preparation may jeopardize project execution. Decide whether you want to receive them daily or in weekly summaries.

Solution principles
Our solutions are founded on 4 principles:

Interoperability: Our solution integrates with third-party tools including project management tools, documentation tools, etc, through e-mails or APIs.
Flexibility: We adapt to your processes and requirements. Our solution is reconfigurable if processes or requirements change, ensuring continuity and longevity.
Continuous improvement: Our solution is offered as Software-as-a-Service, thus new improvements and features are added continuously, in a transparent way.
Innovation: We use the most innovative technology for risk management and prediction, collaborating with the research community to leverage the best ideas.

Overall overview of the application
Beawre Risk Control is offered as Software-as-a-Service (SaaS). This means that the application is hosted by Beawre and is accessible online. Because our business model is based in SaaS, users do not need to install any tools in their system. This also makes maintenance easy and transparent to users. Whenever a new feature or improvement is added to Beawre Risk Control, users do not need to perform any action on their local machines. When they log in to the system, they will be able to see and use the new features instantly.
Landing page and Views
When you connect to Beawre Risk Control, the default landing page is the operational dashboard. However, there are other views that will help you to control risks holistically. The different views are organized in tabs that users can find in the top of the application.
In particular, there are five different tabs:

Home: this is the landing page which shows the operational dashboard. Find more information about the operational dashboard here.
Documents: this view is used to visualize the documentation schedule. Find more information about the "Documents" tab here.
Tasks: this view is used to show tasks from the project schedule. Find more information about the "Tasks" tab here.
Subcontractors: this view is used to list subcontractors and the most relevant metrics about them. Find more information about the "Subcontractors" tab here.
Analytics: this view contains dashboards to analyze historical data. Find more information about the "Analytics" tab here.

First steps
Starting to use Beawre Risk Control is straightforward. Make sure the admin of the system has created new credentials for you and passed them to you through a secure channel.
Please follow these steps:

Start your browser (We recommend Google Chrome or Mozilla Firefox; other browsers may not support some functionalities of the tool or may not work properly).
Insert the following URL: vfr.beawre.com
Enter your credentials

You can start using Beawre Risk Control!
Users and Roles
Beawre Risk Control allows an unlimited number of users to interact in order to efficiently manage the review and approval of documents. Different users may play different roles and observe different functionality in our solution.
Any organization will have a special user role with the rights to manage the organization: the Administrator. This role has privileges to manage all the other users. Apart from the Administrator there may be many other roles, such as VFR Owner, Document Controller, Project Controller, Project Management Team, Subcontractor, etc. Our tool allows the Administrator to define as many roles as necessary and define privileges for each role.
Managing users and roles
As an administrator of the tool you may be able to manage users and roles. In order to do so, please select the option “Privileges Control” in the menu on the top right corner.
In the new view, you will see different subtabs:

Users: in the User tab you will be able to manage users. As an administrator, you can see all the users assigned to you. For each user you can assign a group, branch, or link to a subcontractor. Please, see the next bullet points to know more about the meaning of each of these features.
Groups: Groups are the mechanism Beawre Risk Control solution uses to assign privileges to users. Groups represent the different roles that may use the tool. As an administrator you can create as many groups as you need. Think about who needs to use the tool and what actions they need/should be allowed to do and create a group for each role. In the Groups tab you can create multiple groups and specify, for each one, what are the privileges that they need to have. Once you associate a user to a group, this user will inherit all the privileges of the group. Please, note that privileges cannot be assigned to a single user. If there is a user with a unique role such as the general director or quality department director who may need special access to different features, please create a group to represent this role and assign the user to the group.

Notifications system
Beawre Risk Control solution provides a notification system to warn relevant stakeholders about different important events. The notification system is a risk mitigation mechanism. The objective of notifications is to raise awareness to users about relevant events that need to be considered to mitigate imminent risks.
The current Beawre Risk Control solution considers 5 different situations where notifications are sent:

The risk status of a document changes: in particular any document changing from "Low risk" to "Medium Risk", "Medium Risk" to "High Risk" or "High Risk" to "Late" will generate a notification.
A new document is created: the creation of a document will generate a notification.
The deadline of a task changes: if the deadline of a document changes, the system will generate a notification. This usually happens when the project schedule is updated.
Client violates a document review deadline: when the client takes more time than agreed by contract to review a document, the system will generate a notification.
A subcontractor has not submitted a document and the deadline indicates that the risk of not delivering on time grows: the system will generate a notification when a document has not been received from the subcontractor and the risk status changes from "Low Risk" to "Medium Risk".

There are two mechanisms to receive notification:

Through e-mail: Beawre Risk Control will send an e-mail to users when one of the previously defined events happens.
Through the embedded notification system: Beawre Risk Control has a notification system. To see your notifications, click on the bell symbol in the top right corner.

Every user can customize the notification system. In order to customize your preferences, please unfold the notification menu by clicking on the bell symbol in the top right corner, and click on "Settings" in the right corner of the unfolded menu. For each type of notification, users can decide if they want to receive notifications by e-mail ("EMAIL"), through the embedded notification system ("WEBAPP"), both or none.
Customer support and contact
Our Software-as-a-Service solution license includes our customer support to help you get the most out of our services. We have a team of seasoned professionals that will support your activity and work in collaboration with your organization to generate a working solution for the control of construction documentation risk successfully.
If you need support, please contact us at: support@beawre.com
If you detect any aspect in which our solution is malfunctioning, please contact us at the same e-mail. We'll do our best to help you improve your experience with our solution.
If you have suggestions or recommendations, please contact us! It is through feedback from our users that we learn to create an even greater solution.

Operational-Dashboard.html.title: Operational Dashboard
Operational-Dashboard.html.body:
Operational Dashboard
The operational dashboard is the entry point for Beawre Risk Control. In an attempt to make teams more efficient, our solution makes an actionable dashboard the landing page. From this page you can focus on the most relevant documents (typically those with a higher risk status) and get access to their detail immediately by interacting with the dashboard information.
The operational dashboard gives users information on the current status of the operations. It only shows information about documents that have not been finished yet. The purpose of the operational dashboard is to help users prioritize the most relevant actions to avoid documents being late.
To know more about the different plots shown in the operational dashboard, please hover the mouse over the title of the plot and you will obtain a detailed description.

Documents.html.title: Documents
Documents.html.body:
Documentation Schedule
Beawre Risk Control helps you manage the documentation schedule of your project. In the Documents tab you can see all the documents in the documentation schedule. Please note that you can only see the documents you have access to (depending on your role you may not have privileges to see all the documents).
From the Documents tab you can list the documents in the documentation schedule, add new documents or search specific documents and filter them based on multiple criteria, etc. 
Adding a new document
There are different mechanisms to create a new document in the documentation schedule: automatically and manually.
Automatic documentation addition
The easiest mechanism to create a new document in the documentation schedule is to upload the new document in Dymadoc. When Beawre Risk Control receives an e-mail from Dymadoc, it automatically adds the document to the documentation schedule. Note, while this option is transparent to the user, it does not allow Beawre Risk Control to track expected documents that have not been submitted by the subcontractor yet.
Manual documentation addition
In order to add a new document in the documentation schedule manually, please click on Add New Document. This option is important as it allows the Beawre Risk Control tool to know which documents are expected and to warn owners when documents are not yet submitted by subcontractors and approaching their deadlines.
When a document is created manually, Beawre Risk Control requires different information about the document. Our solution shows possible data options to complete the information about the document quickly. Please note that the suggested information is optional and users can type new information in any of the different fields. Also note that some fields are compulsory - marked with a red asterisk. The system will not allow users to create a new document if these fields are not complete.
Information about a document in the documentation schedule
For each document in the documentation schedule list, users can explore related information. The documents list shows:

the title and the id of each document 
the information source from where the information about this document is extracted. There are two options: 
from the former excel files used to manage the documentation schedule and 
from Dymadoc


the field "Concerns", to indicate the content type of the document.
the field "Version", to indicate the most recent version of the document.
the risk status, to indicate the current level of risk of this document. In order to know more about how we calculate the level of risk, please check Section "Risk analysis of a document" below.

In additon, if you click in the + symbol appearing on the left of each document name and id, you will unfold further document information.
In particular, you can see:

All the existing versions of a particular document.
Statistics about a document. You can hover on each value to see the specific meaning of the statistics displayed in the user interface and, when relevant, information about how they have been calculated.
The full reference of the document.
For each version, the current status of the version. There are several steps a particular version of a document needs to go through. If a step has already taken place, there will be a check next to the step and the actual date when the step happened will be shown. In some cases, this information will not be available and the system will indicate this displaying "Not available". If the step has not taken place yet, the date will not be shown, and there will be a number indicating the position in the process of the next expected step.
The deadline for the document. This information can only be seen if the document was linked to a task in the project schedule.

Search in the documentation schedule
In order to look for a particular document or set of documents, the system provides two different mechanisms for searching: a basic search mechanism and an advanced one.
Please note that the search function is one of the essential features of this system. Searching for specific documents does not only constrain the list of documents visible in the document schedule, but it also affects the data taken into consideration in the ANALYTICS tab. This means that by executing different search queries, it is possible to visually explore different subsets of data through the plots represented in the analytics dashboard.
Basic search mechanism
For a quick search, the basic search mechanism allows users to search any keyword or set of keywords across all the information related to a document. This search is useful for a quick exploration or when users look for some information but they are not sure about the specific field that contains that information. The mechanism is simple as users only need to type relevant words they are interested in and press enter or click in the lens icon.
In order to see all the documents again, users can press the X symbol on the right of the search bar.
Advanced search mechanism
There are situations where users may need to use very precise criteria to filter the documents they are interested in or users may need to repeat certain queries very often. For those cases, the system provides an Advanced Search mode. To access the advanced search please click on "Show Advanced Search".
Advanced search allows you to visually create any logic expression on the different attributes related to a document. A logic expression is composed of conditions on the data attributes (e.g. "VISA result equal to ACC", "Document type different from PZ" or "Risk status equal to high risk"), and a set of three operators (AND, OR, NOT) to combine multiple conditions.
In order to create multiple conditions, users can click on + Add rule. More than one rule need to be linked through an OR operator or an AND operator. With an OR operator the expression is true if at least one of the conditions is true. With an AND operator the expression is true only if all the conditions are true. Users can select whether they want to use the OR or the AND operator by clicking the corresponding boxes. Users may also be interested in finding documents for which the expression does not hold true. In those cases, they can click in the NOT box.
In addition, different expressions with multiple conditions can also be combined to create any logical expression. To create a new expression with new conditions, click on + Add group.
In order to remove the filters on the whole documentation schedule, please click the Reset button.
Please, note that depending on the complexity of a query, its execution may take up to several minutes.
Saving search queries
In case a user wants to reuse the same advanced search several times the system allows users to save their search queries. In order to do so, please click on "Save Search" once the search expression is completed and give a name to that search expression. 
The saved search expression will appear below. If you want to use the search, you just need to click on the saved search expression to re-execute it as many times as necessary.
Actions on documentation
Edit document
FUNCTIONALITY NOT READY YET
Link to DyMaDoc
When the DYMADOC option is written in white letters with a dark grey background, users can click on it and they will be redirected to the Dymadoc page containing that particular document.
When this option is deactivated it means that the Beawre Control Risk system has not received any e-mail from Dymadoc about that particular document. Therefore, the system does not have a link to that document. 
Linking documents to tasks in the project schedule
Documents can be linked to project schedule tasks by clicking on the Assign task option. A new window will unfold where tasks can be linked to documents. A document can be linked to more than one task. In such a case, the deadline for that document will be the earliest of all the deadlines established by all the tasks the document is associated to.
Delete document
In order to delete a document from the documentation schedule, please click on Delete.
Risk Analysis of a document
In order to predict the performance of a current document we learn from the historical data, looking for those documents that are similar to the current document and making a prediction based on the performance of these documents.
In particular, we provide algorithms that compare the evolution of the current document and look in historical data for documents with similar behavior. For this, the system uses a sequence matching algorithms to calculate the distance between several documents. Once distances are calculated, we use them to predict different statistics using inverse distance weighted interpolations. In order to reduce the number of documents considered and increase affinity, we first look for documents of the same subcontractor, type and phase. We also take into consideration the version number, as documents usually present different behaviors depending on whether this is the first version (1.0) of a document or a refinement of a previous version.
In particular, we predict:

The expected number of iterations a document will perform based on the most similar documents.
The dates for each remaining step and whether the last predicted step will respect the deadline established by the task the document is linked to.

Based on the predicted date, we define the level of risk based on two predefined thresholds (X and Y):

Low risk: the predicted date for the documents to be reviewed and approved is at least X days before the deadline. By default, X is equal to 30 days. This value can be modified if necessary.
Medium risk: the predicted date for the documents to be reviewed and approved is between X and Y days before the deadline. By default, Y is equal to 10 days. This value can be modified if necessary.
High risk: the predicted date for the documents to be reviewed and approved is later than Y days before the deadline. 

When a document is not ready by the deadline required by the related task in the project schedule, the risk of not having the document ready by the deadline is not relevant anymore and we label the document as Late.
Once a document is completed, the system considers two different labels:

Completed: if the document finished before or on the deadline.
Completed Late: if the document finished after the deadline.

Exporting the documentation schedule
The system allows users to export the documentation schedule in excel format. In order to export the documentation schedule, please click on ... next to Add New Document + button. Then, click on "Save in Excel format".

Tasks-in-the-Project-Schedule.html.title: Tasks & Project Schedule
Tasks-in-the-Project-Schedule.html.body:
Tasks in the Project Schedule
Beawre Risk Control always has a project schedule uploaded to the system. This project schedule is considered by the system to be the current valid project schedule and the one used to compute the risk status of all documents, once they have been linked to a task.
When we click the TASKS tab in the top of the screen, users can see a view that allows them to see information about the project schedule and the level of risk with respect to each task and linked documents.
Information about a task in the project schedule
TO BE FINISHED
Updating the project schedule
The project schedule can be updated at any time, by uploading a new version and replacing the previous one. This operation can be done at any time and as many times as necessary. The system also allows you to perform what-if analysis, i.e. check how changes in the project schedule may impact the risk status of current and future documents considered in the project schedule.
To update a project schedule or study the potential impact of changes, please press Upload Project Schedule +.  
What-if analysis of project schedule changes impact
Before approving a new version of the project schedule, the owner of the project schedule or other users may be interested in understanding the effect of different changes in the project schedule on the risk status of the documents related to different tasks.
Beawre Risk Control allows users to upload a new file and perform an automated analysis of the differences between different project schedule versions.
When users press Upload Project Schedule + a new form will open called "Upload Project Schedule". This form shows a process with 7 different steps: (1) Waiting, (2) Uploading file, (3) Calculating risks, (4) Finding differences, (5) Revising changes, (6) Commiting changes and (7) Finished.
Here, we discuss the different steps related to what-if analysis:

Waiting: in this initial step, the system is waiting for the user to upload the new project schedule file to be inspected and compared with the current project schedule in the system. Users can drag and drop files from the file system browser (e.g. Explorer in Windows or Finder in Mac OS) or they can click in the box and a pop-up window will allow them to select the file to be uploaded to Beawre's system.
Uploading file: once the file has been selected, the system automatically moves to the next step and starts uploading the file. This step includes uploading the file to Beawre's server, inserting each element of the project schedule into the new database in production, and preparing the data for risk status calculation and comparison. Please note that this process can take from several seconds to several minutes, depending on the size of the project schedule.
Calculating risks: once the file has been uploaded and prepared for the operation, Beawre Risk Control will automatically move to the next step, where risks will be recalculated for all documents and tasks with the new project schedule file. Please note that this process can take from several seconds to several minutes, depending on the size of the project schedule and the documentation schedule.
Finding differences: once risk status has been calculated for each document and task, all the fields of each task are compared with the fields of the same task in the project schedule in the system. Risk status of the task will also be compared. Once the comparison is done, results of the comparison are displayed in the window for users to inspect.
Revising changes: once differences are found by the system, users can now visually explore all the differences between the previous and the new project schedules. Notably, they can also inspect changes in the risk status of tasks and understand what tasks are affected by the changes and what documents are impacted by the update.

We describe the remaining steps in the following subsection.
Please, note that this process can be cancelled at any time pressing Cancel upload process.
Confirming project schedule update
After inspection, users have the possibility to indicate to the system that the previous project schedule is to be replaced by the new one. In order to perform this action, please, press Commit changes button. Otherwise, if you prefer to keep the current project schedule, please press Cancel upload process button.
Search in the task list
The search mechanism for tasks in the project schedule are analogous to those used for documents in the documentation schedule, including a basic search capability and an advanced search. 
Basic search mechanism
For a quick search, the basic search mechanism allows users to search any keyword or set of keywords across all the information related to a task. This search is useful for a quick exploration or when users look for some information but they are not sure about the specific field that contains that information. The mechanism is simple as users only need to type relevant words they are interested in and press enter or click the lens icon.
In order to see all the tasks again, users can press the X symbol to the right of the search bar.
Advanced search mechanism
There are situations where users may need to use very precise criteria to filter the tasks they are interested in or users may need to repeat certain queries very often. For those cases, the system provides an Advanced Search mode. To access to the advanced search please click on "Show Advanced Search".
Advanced search allows you to visually create any logic expression on the different attributes related to a task in the project schedule. A logic expression is composed of conditions on the data attributes (e.g. "Baseline start after a particular date", "Activity ID contains 4580" or "Only tasks linked to documents"), and a set of three operators (AND, OR, NOT) to combine multiple conditions.
In order to create multiple conditions, users can click on + Add rule. More than one rule need to be linked through an OR operator or an AND operator. With an OR operator the expression is true if at least one of the conditions is true. With an AND operator, the expression is true only if all the conditions are true. Users can select whether they want to use the OR or the AND operator by clicking the corresponding boxes. Users may also be interested in finding tasks for which the expression does not hold true. In those cases, they can click in the NOT box.
Different expressions with multiple conditions can be also combined to create any logical expression. To create a new expression with new conditions, click on + Add group.
In order to remove the filters on the whole task list, please click Reset button.
Please, note that depending on the complexity of a query, its execution may take up to several minutes.

Analytics-Dashboard.html.title: Analytics Dashboard
Analytics-Dashboard.html.body:
Analytics Dashboard
The Analytics tab allows users to perform analytics on past data that are useful for decision making. Please, hover over the different plots in the Analytics tab to get a detailed description of each plot. 
On the right part of the screen, users can find a menu with all the displayed plots. Clicking any of the options of the menu will take you to the corresponding plot.
Note that the Analytics tab is connected to the Documents tab. Data shown in the dashboards corresponds to the list displayed in the documentation schedule. If we apply a constraint through a set of rules in the search bar, the same rules will be shown in the Analytics tab, and plotted data will only correspond to this subset of documents. Analogously, if we apply a constraint in the search bar in the Analytics tab, when we click the Documents tab we will only see the list of documents corresponding to the subset of documents resulting from applying this constraint. In other words, the search tool remains consistent across tabs.
In order to know more about the search capabilities of our system, please refer to the Documents tab section's help option.
We would like to note that this feature is powerful for analytics as you can focus your analysis to any interesting subset of documents at any time.
